says that the
report is "not a truthful or
accurate portrayal

02:00.653 --> 02:06.559 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of the conversation" and that
the president
never asked anyone to end any
investigation.

02:06.593 --> 02:09.295 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For more, we turn now to Matt
Apuzzo of The
Times.

02:09.329 --> 02:11.297 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Matt, thanks for joining us.

02:11.331 --> 02:14.634 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Tell me what the significance of
this memo
is.

02:14.667 --> 02:18.471 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MATT APUZZO, The New York Times:
Well, the
significance of the memo, of
course, is just

02:18.505 --> 02:24.677 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
not -- you know, just last week,
the president
fired Jim Comey, the FBI
director, and the

02:24.711 --> 02:26.546 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
stories kept changing.

02:26.579 --> 02:32.619 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And one of the back-and-forths
has been, there
was this conversation between
Comey and the

02:32.652 --> 02:36.256 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
president in which the president
said, "I
want your loyalty."

02:36.289 --> 02:37.790 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And Comey wouldn't give him his
loyalty.

02:37.824 --> 02:40.493 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And then the question became,
well, is that
why he got fired?

02:40.527 --> 02:44.397 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And you will remember that the
president tweeted
out, oh, Jim Comey better hope
there's not

02:44.430 --> 02:46.466 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
tapes of our conversations.

02:46.499 --> 02:52.405 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Well, it turns out Jim Comey was
keeping memos
and was keeping contemporaneous
notes on every

02:52.438 --> 02:56.109 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
interaction he had with the
president and
was becoming very concerned
about some of

02:56.142 --> 02:58.378 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
those interactions and sought to
document
those going forward.

02:58.411 --> 03:01.381 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN YANG: And he showed these
to colleagues
at the time, right?

03:01.414 --> 03:03.783 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MATT APUZZO: He showed them to
colleagues.

03:03.816 --> 03:06.085 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
He provided them with copies.

03:06.119 --> 03:12.425 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, you know, my colleague Mike
Schmidt,
who was the primary reporter on
this story,

03:12.458 --> 03:14.027 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
talked to people who had seen
the memos.

03:14.060 --> 03:17.297 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That quote you read was read to
us.

03:17.330 --> 03:21.467 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This is -- this is something --
this is a
real -- this is a real dramatic
turn in this

03:21.501 --> 03:28.074 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
story about, why did Donald
Trump fire Jim
Comey, and what is Donald Trump
attempting

03:28.107 --> 03:33.680 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to do in terms of influencing
the investigation
into his campaign and his
associates?

03:33.713 --> 03:37.917 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Matt, tell us more
about the specific
meeting that you wrote -- that
is written

03:37.951 --> 03:41.854 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
about The Times, just the story
that was posted
just a little bit OK?

03:41.888 --> 03:46.993 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MATT APUZZO: Yes, we know it's a
February
14 meeting, a private meting
between the president

03:47.026 --> 03:49.762 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and the FBI director, Jim Comey.

03:49.796 --> 03:55.735 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, in it, the president
mentions how concerned
he is about leaks and actually
makes this

03:55.768 --> 04:00.039 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
remark that, maybe we need to
throw a couple
of reporters in jail anyone to
sort of send

04:00.073 --> 04:01.975 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
a message.

04:02.008 --> 04:05.111 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And then they -- the president
brings up Michael
Flynn and says, look, I think
he's a really

04:05.144 --> 04:06.446 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
good guy.

04:06.479 --> 04:08.948 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And if you can see your way
clear about it,
just let this go.

04:08.982 --> 04:10.116 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Let Michael Flynn go.

04:10.149 --> 04:11.818 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
He's a good man.

04:11.851 --> 04:17.023 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Now, Comey went back,
apparently, and documented
that conversation.

04:17.056 --> 04:22.562 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And one thing that's interesting
about Comey
is, 10 years ago, Comey was at
the center

04:22.595 --> 04:27.267 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of another major issue where he
described
this dramatic showdown with the
Bush administration

04:27.300 --> 04:28.401 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
over warrantless wiretapping.

04:28.434 --> 04:31.070 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And the White House denied that
conversation.

04:31.104 --> 04:36.175 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it turned out that it was
the FBI director
at the time, Bob Mueller, kept
his contemporaneous

04:36.209 --> 04:38.678 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
notes, and that backed up
Comey's account.

04:38.711 --> 04:42.015 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, in a lot of ways, this is
what's old is
new again.

04:42.048 --> 04:46.853 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The FBI director was keeping
contemporaneous
notes on his conversations with
the president.

04:46.886 --> 04:48.521 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN YANG: And not just this
conversation,
Matt.

04:48.554 --> 04:52.759 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Do we think he kept these notes
throughout
his conversations with the
president?

04:52.792 --> 04:56.696 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MATT APUZZO: Our understanding
is, he documented
every interaction, every meeting
and every

04:56.729 --> 05:01.834 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
phone call with the president
and, on a number
of occasions, expressed concerns
about the

05:01.868 --> 05:07.040 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
about the emerging relationship
between the
White House and the FBI
director.

05:07.073 --> 05:11.110 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Remember, the FBI director is
normally kind
of an arms-length relationship
with the White

05:11.144 --> 05:16.316 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
House for precisely this reason,
because,
sometimes, you know, the FBI can
be investigating

05:16.349 --> 05:19.018 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
