war crimes
prosecutions.

26:51.643 --> 26:56.147 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
North Korea has become the prime
suspect in
the global cyber-attack.

26:56.181 --> 27:02.153 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
A growing number of
cyber-security experts
now say the lines in the
ransomware code are

27:02.187 --> 27:07.425 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
identical to lines in the code
used by previous
hackers linked to the North.

27:07.459 --> 27:09.461 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And, they say, there are other
clues.

27:09.494 --> 27:12.931 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ERIC CHIEN, Symantec Researcher:
It's a bit
unclear on what their ultimate
motivation

27:12.964 --> 27:19.437 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
here is, but it does seem pretty
clear that
this is not the kind of thing a
very professional

27:19.471 --> 27:22.007 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
cyber-criminal would do.

27:22.040 --> 27:27.245 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You know, guys who are involved
in these types
of schemes like to run just
under the radar.

27:27.278 --> 27:30.815 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You want to infect as many
machines as possible,
but still be under the radar.

27:30.849 --> 27:36.621 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: The attack has
infected thousands
of computers and servers in
about 150 countries,

27:36.655 --> 27:41.459 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
but the Department of Homeland
Security says
only a handful were in the
United States.

27:41.493 --> 27:46.464 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Back in this country, Senator
John Cornyn
now says he's not interested in
being FBI

27:46.498 --> 27:47.866 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
director.

27:47.899 --> 27:50.001 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
The Texas Republican was
interviewed for the
job over the weekend.

27:50.035 --> 27:53.371 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Today, in a statement, he said
he'd rather
stay in the Senate.

27:53.405 --> 27:58.343 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Yesterday, South Carolina
Congressman Trey
Gowdy withdrew from
consideration.

27:58.376 --> 28:04.115 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A new federal study finds that
one in every
five middle and high school
students complained

28:04.149 --> 28:06.551 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
of being bullied in 2015.

28:06.584 --> 28:12.624 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That's despite the fact that the
overall problem
improved over the last decade;
21 percent

28:12.657 --> 28:19.130 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of students ages 12 to 18 said
they were bullied
in 2015, and reports of sexual
assaults on

28:19.164 --> 28:26.838 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
college campuses nearly tripled
between 2001
and 2014, to 6,700.

28:26.871 --> 28:31.409 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Advances in reducing the number
of Americans
without health insurance have
stalled.

28:31.443 --> 28:36.214 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Centers for Disease Control
and Prevention
says the number last year was
unchanged at

28:36.247 --> 28:39.184 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
28.6 million.

28:39.217 --> 28:44.789 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That ends five years of coverage
gains under
the Affordable Care Act, or
Obamacare.

28:44.823 --> 28:47.625 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And on Wall Street, stocks had a
lackluster
day.

28:47.659 --> 28:53.531 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The Dow Jones industrial average
lost two
points to close above 20979.

28:53.565 --> 28:59.037 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The Nasdaq rose 20 points, and
the S&amp;P 500
slipped one point.

28:59.070 --> 29:04.409 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Still to come on the "NewsHour":
Turkey's
president visits the White House
amid strained

29:04.442 --> 29:10.749 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
relations between the two
allies; the pushback
against requiring seat belts on
school buses;

29:10.782 --> 29:22.827 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
and much more.

29:22.861 --> 29:27.165 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
President Trump welcomed Turkish
President
Recep Tayyip Erdogan to the
White House today,

29:27.198 --> 29:31.636 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
amid heightened tensions for the
longtime
and now troubled allies.

29:31.669 --> 29:35.273 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Chief foreign affairs
correspondent Margaret
Warner begins our coverage.

29:35.306 --> 29:40.345 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
MARGARET WARNER: Despite
tensions between
Washington and Ankara, it was
best foot forward

29:40.378 --> 29:44.182 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
from both leaders at the White
House this
afternoon, at least in public.

29:44.215 --> 29:46.951 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DONALD TRUMP, President of the
United States:
I look forward to working
together with President

29:46.985 --> 29:50.488 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Erdogan on achieving peace and
security in
the Middle East.

29:50.522 --> 29:53.324 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RECEP TAYYIP ERDOGAN, Turkish
President (through
translator): President Trump's
recent election

29:53.358 --> 29:58.463 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
victory has led to the awakening
of a new
set of aspirations and
expectations and hopes

29:58.496 --> 30:00.265 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in our region.

30:00.298 --> 30:04.002 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: But relations
between the
two NATO allies have
deteriorated sharply.

30:04.035 --> 30:10.975 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Former President Obama grew
critical of President
Recep Tayyip Erdogan's
increasingly authoritarian

30:11.009 --> 30:12.777 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
ways.

30:12.811 --> 30:18.716 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
President Trump came to office
calling for
improved ties, but tensions
flared again.

30:18.750 --> 30:23.888 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The rawest point of contention,
America's
battlefield partnership with the
Syrian Kurdish

30:23.922 --> 30:26.758 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
militia known as the YPG.

30:26.791 --> 30:30.161 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's the most effective ground
force fighting
ISIS.

30:30.195 --> 30:36.367 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Ankara objects, arguing the YPG
is linked
to Turkey's Kurdish terror group
the PKK.

30:36.401 --> 30:42.006 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But the U.S. announced last week
it will furnish
the YPG with heavier weapons.

30:42.040 --> 30:45.610 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Defense Secretary James Mattis
sought to soften
the blow to Ankara.

30:45.643 --> 30:49.080 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JAMES MATTIS, U.S. Secretary of
Defense: We
are very open to discussions
about options,

30:49.113 --> 30:54.018 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and we will work together, and
we will work
out any of the concerns.

30:54.052 --> 31:00.892 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I am not concerned at all about
the NATO alliance
and the relations between our
nations.

31:00.925 --> 31:06.931 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: Today, Mr.
Trump cited the
PKK, alongside ISIS, as a
regional terror

31:06.965 --> 31:10.869 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
group, but he didn't mention the
YPG.

31:10.902 --> 31:14.372 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Erdogan said neither group
deserves a future
in the region.

31:14.405 --> 31:18.276 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RECEP TAYYIP ERDOGAN (through
translator):
Taking the YPG and its allies in
the region

31:18.309 --> 31:22.981 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
into consideration will never be
accepted,
and it is going to be against a
global agreement

31:23.014 --> 31:24.816 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
that we have reached.

31:24.849 --> 31:29.320 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: Last month,
Turkey conducted
cross-border airstrikes against
the YPG, killing

31:29.354 --> 31:31.189 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
more than 20.

31:31.222 --> 31:37.128 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Internally, Washington is
dismayed by Erdogan's
crackdown on domestic dissent,
especially

31:37.161 --> 31:39.430 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
since last year's abortive coup.

31:39.464 --> 31:46.371 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Some 47,000 people have been
arrested, and
another 100,000 fired from
government posts.

31:46.404 --> 31:52.510 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Ankara accuses self-exiled
Muslim cleric Fethullah
Gulen of orchestrating the coup
attempt and

31:52.543 --> 31:56.180 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is furious that the U.S. hasn't
extradited
him.

31:56.214 --> 32:01.419 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
All this follows a referendum
last month greatly
expanding Erdogan's powers.

32:01.452 --> 32:04.455 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The result sparked widespread
protests.

32:04.489 --> 32:09.193 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
European monitors criticized it
as below international
standards.

32:09.227 --> 32:15.066 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Mr. Trump telephoned Erdogan to
congratulate
him, however, something no other
Western leader

32:15.099 --> 32:16.067 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
did.

32:16.100 --> 32:18.903 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," I'm
Margaret Warner.

32:18.937 --> 32:22.240 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN YANG: And now Jeffrey Brown
takes it
from there.

32:22.273 --> 32:25.410 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: So, what is
likely to come
of the Trump-Erdogan meeting?

32:25.443 --> 32:28.313 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And how serious are the tensions
between the
two allies?

32:28.346 --> 32:33.651 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
To help us answer those
questions, we turn
to Soner Cagaptay of the
Washington Institute

32:33.685 --> 32:35.219 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
for Near East Policy.

32:35.253 --> 32:39.257 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He is the author of "The New
Sultan: Erdogan
and the Crisis of Modern
Turkey."

32:39.290 --> 32:44.729 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And Ali Cinar, president of the
Turkish Heritage
Organization, who's just come
from a meeting

32:44.762 --> 32:45.797 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
with President Erdogan.

32:45.830 --> 32:48.066 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, let me start with you, Ali
Cinar.

32:48.099 --> 32:53.771 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Let's get right to that question
of the main
dispute, the U.S. decision to
arm a Kurdish

32:53.805 --> 32:55.506 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
militia fighting in Syria.

32:55.540 --> 32:58.242 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
How much anger did that provoke
in Turkey?

32:58.276 --> 33:03.414 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ALI CINAR, President, Turkish
Heritage Organization:
Well, it was -- it was a really
bad perception

33:03.448 --> 33:09.754 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
from the Turkey side, because,
since the terror
attacks increase in Turkey, the
Turkish people

33:09.787 --> 33:14.359 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
got upset with United States,
since U.S. support
PYG.

33:14.392 --> 33:21.199 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, the meeting today between
President Trump
and Erdogan mainly focused on
the PYG issue

33:21.232 --> 33:22.734 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and extradition of Fethullah
Gulen.

33:22.767 --> 33:27.105 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, there were two important,
major issues
that they discussed noontime.

33:27.138 --> 33:32.810 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And, Soner
Cagaptay, what did
President Erdogan want from this
meeting?

33:32.844 --> 33:34.612 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And do we know what he got?

33:34.645 --> 33:36.481 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SONER CAGAPTAY, Director,
Turkish Research
Program, Washington Institute
for Near East

33:36.514 --> 33:39.417 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Policy: I think he got half of
what he wanted
already, which was to be invited
to Washington.

33:39.450 --> 33:44.922 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
He just won a contested
referendum that has
made him executive-style
president.

33:44.956 --> 33:50.228 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
As I highlight in my latest
book, "The New
Sultan," Turkey is a very
divided country,

33:50.261 --> 33:52.997 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
largely as a result of Erdogan's
political
trajectory.

33:53.031 --> 33:56.601 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Half of the country loves him,
and the other
half hates him.

33:56.634 --> 34:00.605 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For the half that loathes him,
they didn't
see the referendum as free and
fair.

34:00.638 --> 34:05.543 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And Erdogan was aching to get a
Western leader
to invite him, so he could
affirm his victory

34:05.576 --> 34:07.278 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
as he saw it.

34:07.311 --> 34:10.982 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, by the mere fact that he was
invited to
the White House, he got more
than half he

34:11.015 --> 34:12.750 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
wanted.

34:12.784 --> 34:15.820 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
On top of it, I think, today, he
wanted to
see some concessions regarding
the Kurdish

34:15.853 --> 34:20.425 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
issue and the U.S. policy on the
Kurdish issue,
and he may have gotten that as
well.

34:20.458 --> 34:25.396 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think that the deal President
Trump offered
to Turkish President Erdogan is
that the United

34:25.430 --> 34:31.002 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
States will look -- wants Turkey
to look the
other way as Washington arms the
Syrian Kurds

34:31.035 --> 34:32.837 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to take Raqqa from ISIS.

34:32.870 --> 34:38.109 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In return, Washington is willing
to look the
other way as Turkey fights the
Syrian Kurds'

34:38.142 --> 34:42.013 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ally PKK In Iraq and elsewhere
where it has
strongholds.

34:42.046 --> 34:47.118 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Ali Cinar, do you
see him,
the president, Erdogan, having
gotten anything

34:47.151 --> 34:52.623 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
out of this meeting, because the
U.S. has
stood by its decision to arm the
Kurds?

34:52.657 --> 34:54.392 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ALI CINAR: Right.

34:54.425 --> 34:58.296 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I mean, I don't think you will
see in the
short term -- but what President
Trump said,

34:58.329 --> 35:06.270 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
also, we are going to also let
some Turkish
government use some war -- I
mean, guns to

35:06.304 --> 35:11.642 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Turkish government, meaning that
Trump said,
we are going to arm Turkey, too.

35:11.676 --> 35:13.444 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It was an interesting statement.

35:13.478 --> 35:19.984 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, also, it seems like United
States is
going to use PYG on the Raqqa
operation, but

35:20.017 --> 35:27.058 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for the other ground operations,
there might
be a collaboration between
Turkey and United

35:27.091 --> 35:28.960 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
States.

35:28.993 --> 35:33.998 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, it's difficult to see right
now, but,
in the long term, you might see
a better cooperation

35:34.031 --> 35:35.867 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
between the two countries.

35:35.900 --> 35:39.070 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: What about,
staying with you,
Ali Cinar, on the question of
Fethullah Gulen?

35:39.103 --> 35:42.540 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
There, too, Turkey seems to have
been rebuffed.

35:42.573 --> 35:45.209 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
ALI CINAR: Yes.

35:45.243 --> 35:51.649 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I mean, the problem is, right
now, the U.S.
side says, OK, Turkey needs to
respect our

35:51.682 --> 35:54.552 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
legal system and process.

35:54.585 --> 36:00.858 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But now Erdogan is insisting
that that was
a treaty agreement, extradition
agreement

36:00.892 --> 36:04.295 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
between Turkey and the United
States signed
in 1979.

36:04.328 --> 36:11.335 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And at least Turkey is asking to
detain Fethullah
Gulen, and the U.S. side is not
doing it right

36:11.369 --> 36:12.336 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
now.

36:12.370 --> 36:15.406 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
So I don't we will see a
solution on this.

36:15.439 --> 36:18.042 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But Turkey continues to insist
on Fethullah
Gulen.

36:18.075 --> 36:22.313 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Soner Cagaptay,
you mentioned
the human rights issues earlier.

36:22.346 --> 36:25.449 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think that they didn't come
up, at least
publicly.

36:25.483 --> 36:27.485 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Did that surprise you?

36:27.518 --> 36:29.320 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Should it have come up?

36:29.353 --> 36:32.957 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SONER CAGAPTAY: Probably not,
because Turkey
is a large country, and the
Turks don't like

36:32.990 --> 36:35.259 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to be lectured, especially by
outsiders.

36:35.293 --> 36:40.031 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think, if it came up, I would
have preferred
that it came out in private
meetings.

36:40.064 --> 36:41.032 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
This is an important issue.

36:41.065 --> 36:44.168 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And it's not about selling
American values.

36:44.202 --> 36:47.939 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
President Erdogan in Turkey has
won elections
on a platform of economic good
governance,

36:47.972 --> 36:52.877 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
but also demonizing groups that
do not vote
for him, ranging from leftists
to liberals

36:52.910 --> 36:54.812 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to Kurds.

36:54.845 --> 36:58.282 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
At a result, the very is very
deeply polarized
country, as I write in my book
"The New Sultan."

36:58.316 --> 37:03.688 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, at the same time, this very
deeply polarized
country is now in a state of
crisis, where

37:03.721 --> 37:08.492 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
half believe that they live in
heaven, and
the other half believe that they
live in hell.

37:08.526 --> 37:10.294 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
That is not sustainable.

37:10.328 --> 37:15.299 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Turkey is a key ally for the
United States
because it borders Iran, Iraq,
Syria, ISIS,

37:15.333 --> 37:17.068 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and Russia across the Black Sea.

37:17.101 --> 37:21.339 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Whatever U.S. policies are
regarding those
countries or entities, they're
much easier

37:21.372 --> 37:23.107 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
with Turkey.

37:23.140 --> 37:26.811 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But they're easier with Turkey,
which is a
stable country, not a country
which is in

37:26.844 --> 37:27.945 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
crisis.

37:27.979 --> 37:29.747 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Erdogan's trajectory has put
Turkey into a
crisis.

37:29.780 --> 37:33.384 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think that the human
rights issues are
not about selling American
values.

37:33.417 --> 37:36.621 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They're about making sure that
Turkey remains
a stable place.

37:36.654 --> 37:41.892 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the only way for that is, of
course, for
President Erdogan to depolarize
Turkey's landscape,

37:41.926 --> 37:44.762 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
as well as to become a unifier,
after having
won the referendum.

37:44.795 --> 37:47.531 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I wish and hope that that came
up in the conversation.

37:47.565 --> 37:50.468 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: So, Ali Cinar,
finally, to
the extent that today was -- a
big part of

37:50.501 --> 37:55.306 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
today was about trying to mend
fences in what
has been a very tense time,
where do things

37:55.339 --> 37:57.108 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
go from here?

37:57.141 --> 38:02.647 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ALI CINAR: I mean, they are
going to meet
also in Europe for the NATO
summit, and this

38:02.680 --> 38:05.950 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
talk will continue for their
next meeting.

38:05.983 --> 38:11.889 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But what I see is right now
fighting against
ISIS are the most important
common strategy

38:11.922 --> 38:13.824 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
for both countries.

38:13.858 --> 38:19.563 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, hopefully, the Turkish army
and the Pentagon
can closely work together, and
then move forward.

38:19.597 --> 38:25.269 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Otherwise, it will be a
disaster, if they
don't coordinate in the region,
since Turkey

38:25.303 --> 38:28.839 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
is still upset on the U.S.
support to PYG.

38:28.873 --> 38:32.743 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, hopefully, the dialogue will
continue
between the two countries.

38:32.777 --> 38:34.178 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
That's my hope.

38:34.211 --> 38:36.180 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Ali Cinar, Soner
Cagaptay,
thank you both very much.

38:36.213 --> 38:38.582 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
SONER CAGAPTAY: Thank you.

38:38.616 --> 38:46.457 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ALI CINAR: Thank you.

38:46.490 --> 38:51.262 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JOHN YANG: Stay with us.

38:51.295 --> 38:55.966 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Coming up on the "NewsHour": a
view from Colorado
-- the state's Democratic
governor weighs

38:56.000 --> 38:58.536 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
in on the health care battle.

38:58.569 --> 39:03.074 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But first: Every day, millions
of parents
put their children on buses for
the trip to

39:03.107 --> 39:04.375 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
school.

39:04.408 --> 39:07.678 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Statistically, buses remain the
safest way
to make that trip.

39:07.712 --> 39:10.014 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
But fatal accidents do happen.

39:10.047 --> 39:15.686 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Just yesterday, an 11-year-old
boy died in
East Texas when the bus he was
riding on collided

39:15.720 --> 39:18.155 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
with another vehicle and rolled
over.

39:18.189 --> 39:22.426 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Special correspondent list Lisa
Stark reports
that a record number of states
are trying

39:22.460 --> 39:27.698 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to improve school bus safety,
part of our
weekly series, Making the Grade.

39:27.732 --> 39:30.868 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MAN: Get in and put your seat
belts on, guys.

39:30.901 --> 39:36.073 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA STARK: This is a sight you
rarely see
on a school bus: students
buckling themselves

39:36.107 --> 39:37.241 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
in.

39:37.274 --> 39:39.076 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
STUDENT: You feel safer when you
put your
seat belt on.

39:39.110 --> 39:40.378 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KRIS HAFEZIZADEH, Transportation
Director,
Austin Independent School
District: The school

39:40.411 --> 39:44.682 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
bus transportation, we carry the
most precious
cargo, right?

39:44.715 --> 39:49.086 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA STARK: Kris Hafezizadeh is
the director
of transportation for the
Austin, Texas, school

39:49.120 --> 39:50.955 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
district.

39:50.988 --> 39:55.593 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Five years ago, the district
decided every
new bus it bought would come
with lap shoulder

39:55.626 --> 40:01.298 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
belts, at an extra $8,000 per
bus, and not
because there had been an
accident.

40:01.332 --> 40:06.270 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KRIS HAFEZIZADEH: We thought
that, you know,
we always ask your kids, when
they get inside

40:06.303 --> 40:07.938 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the car, to put on their seat
belts.

40:07.972 --> 40:13.477 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, to carry the culture inside
our school
buses, it does add to additional
safety.

40:13.511 --> 40:18.482 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA STARK: But most school
districts have
decided against adding seat
belts.

40:18.516 --> 40:25.389 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In Montgomery County, Maryland,
buses carry
100,000 students a day, and
there has never

40:25.423 --> 40:29.126 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
been an accident in which a
student rider
died.

40:29.160 --> 40:34.365 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Buying new buses with seat belts
would cost
an extra $1 million a year.

40:34.398 --> 40:38.202 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Transportation director Todd
Watkins says
it doesn't make fiscal sense.

40:38.235 --> 40:41.839 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Is that a tough position to
take, to try to
explain to people?

40:41.872 --> 40:43.607 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TODD WATKINS, Transportation
Director, Montgomery
County Public Schools: It is,
because when

40:43.641 --> 40:48.045 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
you're talking about anything
that is involving
safety, how can you be against
it?

40:48.078 --> 40:49.814 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And I'm not against it.

40:49.847 --> 40:56.821 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I just don't think it's the best
use of money
right now, because the safety is
at such a

40:56.854 --> 40:58.923 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
high level in school buses as it
is.

40:58.956 --> 41:03.394 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LISA STARK: Twenty-five million
children ride
school buses every day.

41:03.427 --> 41:08.265 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Accidents claim around five to
six lives a
year.

41:08.299 --> 41:13.304 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Statistics show children are
safer riding
to school in a bus than with a
parent.

41:13.337 --> 41:15.072 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
MARK ROSEKIND, Former
Administrator, National
Highway Traffic Safety
Administration: Those

41:15.105 --> 41:18.909 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
big yellow buses are the safest
way for all
of our kids to get to school
every single

41:18.943 --> 41:19.910 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
day.

41:19.944 --> 41:21.712 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The question is, can we make
them safer?

41:21.745 --> 41:25.883 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA STARK: Mark Rosekind headed
up the National
Highway Traffic Safety
Administration, or

41:25.916 --> 41:27.751 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
NHTSA, under President Obama.

41:27.785 --> 41:30.221 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That agency regulates school
buses.

41:30.254 --> 41:36.794 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Rosekind shocked school
officials by advocating
something no other NHTSA
director ever had.

41:36.827 --> 41:42.066 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARK ROSEKIND: Three-point seat
belts should
be the norm on all new school
buses, because

41:42.099 --> 41:44.034 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
we're talking about trying to
save every life.

41:44.068 --> 41:47.204 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LISA STARK: But districts argue
they're getting
a mixed message.

41:47.238 --> 41:52.309 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
There is no federal law
requiring seat belts
on buses, and NHTSA has
concluded -- quote

41:52.343 --> 41:58.215 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
-- "that large school buses
without seat belts
do not pose an unreasonable risk
of death

41:58.249 --> 41:59.483 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
or injury.

41:59.517 --> 42:03.287 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We do not find a safety need for
a federal
mandate."

42:03.320 --> 42:05.222 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARK ROSEKIND: You don't need
the government
to tell you to do this.

42:05.256 --> 42:07.091 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
The technology is available now.

42:07.124 --> 42:11.262 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA STARK: Whenever there's a
tragedy, such
as the Chattanooga crash last
November, which

42:11.295 --> 42:16.634 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
killed six children, there is
always an anguished
debate over seat belts.

42:16.667 --> 42:21.572 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ALLISON STOOS, Accident Victim:
It's so frustrating
to me every time I see another
accident.

42:21.605 --> 42:27.311 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA STARK: Allison Stoos still
bears the
scars of her accident over a
decade ago.

42:27.344 --> 42:32.349 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She was traveling with her
soccer team in
a small bus chartered by her
Texas high school,

42:32.383 --> 42:36.387 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
not built to school bus
standards, but also
without seat belts.

42:36.420 --> 42:40.658 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ALLISON STOOS: The bus swerved,
and that's
pretty much all I remember.

42:40.691 --> 42:43.694 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
LISA STARK: The bus rolled over
on its side.

42:43.727 --> 42:45.329 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Two teammates died.

42:45.362 --> 42:48.532 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Three, including Allison, were
seriously injured.

42:48.566 --> 42:52.503 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She was partially ejected, her
arm trapped
under the bus.

42:52.536 --> 42:56.540 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Countless surgeries later, she
has limited
use of her left arm.

42:56.574 --> 43:01.011 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ALLISON STOOS: The way it's
impacted my life
and all my friends' lives, and
not just the

43:01.045 --> 43:06.784 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
girls on the bus, but our entire
school was
just turned upside down.

43:06.817 --> 43:10.087 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA STARK: Do you think, if you
would had
had a seat belt, it would have
made a difference?

43:10.120 --> 43:14.892 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ALLISON STOOS: Certainly, in my
injury in
our type of wreck, with a
rollover, I definitely

43:14.925 --> 43:16.994 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
think it would have made a
difference.

43:17.027 --> 43:21.198 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA STARK: For decades, school
buses have
been designed to protect riders
through something

43:21.231 --> 43:22.633 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
called compartmentalization.

43:22.666 --> 43:25.269 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
The seats are close together.

43:25.302 --> 43:28.138 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The backs are high and they're
padded.

43:28.172 --> 43:32.476 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This helps keep the student in
the compartment,
if you will, during an accident.

43:32.509 --> 43:38.549 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It works well during front and
rear impacts.

43:38.582 --> 43:43.754 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This crash test shows how
unbelted students
-- that's these test dummies --
stay in their

43:43.787 --> 43:46.924 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
seats after a frontal crash.

43:46.957 --> 43:53.464 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But, in this test, which
simulates a rollover,
very few of the test dummies
stay put.

43:53.497 --> 43:59.570 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Students can also go flying in
violent side-impact
crashes, as shown in this
onboard video.

43:59.603 --> 44:02.139 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
KRISTIN POLAND, National
Transportation Safety
Board: These severe side-impact
crashes and

44:02.172 --> 44:08.045 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
high-speed rollover crashes are
very rare
school bus crashes, but, when
they do happen,

44:08.078 --> 44:10.114 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
we find that the children are
vulnerable.

44:10.147 --> 44:15.119 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA STARK: Lap-shoulder belts
reduce that
vulnerability, according to
Kristin Poland.

44:15.152 --> 44:19.657 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
She's with the National
Transportation Safety
Board, which investigates school
bus crashes.

44:19.690 --> 44:24.695 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KRISTIN POLAND: In this case, we
had a single
vehicle that left the roadway,
impacted a

44:24.728 --> 44:26.563 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
pole, impacted several trees.

44:26.597 --> 44:32.269 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA STARK: This 2014 crash in
Anaheim, California,
injured the driver and nine
students.

44:32.302 --> 44:34.138 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
No one died.

44:34.171 --> 44:38.075 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KRISTIN POLAND: This was the
first crash where
we had a school bus that was
equipped with

44:38.108 --> 44:40.411 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
lap-shoulder belts in all
seating positions.

44:40.444 --> 44:44.581 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA STARK: Poland looked at
what might have
been, if two of the more
seriously injured

44:44.615 --> 44:46.684 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
students were wearing only lap
belts.

44:46.717 --> 44:49.586 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KRISTIN POLAND: Here, we have
the occupants
interacting with each other.

44:49.620 --> 44:51.321 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
LISA STARK: Or no belts at all.

44:51.355 --> 44:54.758 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KRISTIN POLAND: In the unbelted
cases, we
have our occupant that was
seated along the

44:54.792 --> 44:57.828 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
aisle that's come all the way
over and is
now down on the floor.

44:57.861 --> 45:01.165 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The lap-shoulder belts are
giving the greatest
protection, because they are
keeping the body

45:01.198 --> 45:05.869 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
upright, keeping the occupant in
the seating
compartment, keeping the
occupants away from

45:05.903 --> 45:07.705 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
each other.

45:07.738 --> 45:11.408 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA STARK: Only seven states
have school
bus seat belt laws on the books,
but Louisiana

45:11.442 --> 45:15.879 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and Texas have not approved the
funding and
Arkansas' law is brand-new.

45:15.913 --> 45:22.219 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Even advocates will tell you
installing belts
alone isn't enough.

45:22.252 --> 45:27.291 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
A big challenge is ensuring
students wear
them properly, or at all.

45:27.324 --> 45:28.392 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Do you ever ride without it on
the bus?

45:28.425 --> 45:29.393 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
STUDENT: Sometimes.

45:29.426 --> 45:31.128 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
LISA STARK: Why is that?

45:31.161 --> 45:33.530 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STUDENT: Because I feel like --
sometimes,
I forget to put my seat belt on,
sometimes.

45:33.564 --> 45:39.369 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LISA STARK: But Allison says, at
least these
students have an option.

45:39.403 --> 45:44.975 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ALLISON STOOS: I didn't have the
choice to
sit there and buckle myself up
to protect

45:45.008 --> 45:46.777 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
myself.

45:46.810 --> 45:50.380 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA STARK: Allison, with her
dad and others,
helped get the Texas school bus
seat belt

45:50.414 --> 45:52.616 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
law passed in 2007.

45:52.649 --> 45:56.687 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They're still trying to get it
funded.

45:56.720 --> 45:59.757 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Ultimately, money is the biggest
driver.

45:59.790 --> 46:06.330 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Education dollars are scarce,
and few districts
believe it pays to have students
buckle up.

46:06.363 --> 46:16.907 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour" and
Education Week,
I'm Lisa Stark in Austin, Texas.

46:16.940 --> 46:26.984 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: While President
Trump's troubles
over issues continue to dominate
the headlines,

46:27.017 --> 46:31.588 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the battle over the future of
health care
is still brewing in the
background.

46:31.622 --> 46:34.324 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Here again, William Brangham
with that story.

46:34.358 --> 46:37.928 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: With the
passage of the
House Republican bill to repeal
and replace

46:37.961 --> 46:42.499 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
the Affordable Care Act,
President Obama's
signature health care law, the
focus now shifts

46:42.533 --> 46:44.301 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to the U.S. Senate.

46:44.334 --> 46:48.038 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
As part of our ongoing look at
what's at stake
for health care in the U.S., we
are joined

46:48.071 --> 46:51.341 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
now by Democrat John
Hickenlooper, governor
of Colorado.

46:51.375 --> 46:52.342 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Welcome to the "NewsHour."

46:52.376 --> 46:53.443 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
GOV.

46:53.477 --> 46:55.112 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN HICKENLOOPER (D), Colorado:
Nice to be
here.

46:55.145 --> 46:56.747 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: So, before we
talk about
health care, can I just get your
reaction

46:56.780 --> 47:00.918 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to these latest revelations
about the president
and his dealings with the FBI?

47:00.951 --> 47:01.919 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
GOV.

47:01.952 --> 47:02.986 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JOHN HICKENLOOPER: Sure.

47:03.020 --> 47:04.888 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And I -- you know, I think it
shows two things.

47:04.922 --> 47:08.826 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, you know, I got into
politics, I became
mayor of Denver when I was 50.

47:08.859 --> 47:14.298 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And I made all kinds of
mistakes, because
being an executive in business
is very different

47:14.331 --> 47:15.699 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
than an executive in public
life.

47:15.732 --> 47:17.501 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So I kept doing dumb things.

47:17.534 --> 47:22.172 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But this really kind of shows
how much power
the president of the United
States has.

47:22.206 --> 47:27.377 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, obviously, he can make
decisions to declassify
information and share it as he
wants.

47:27.411 --> 47:31.114 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But it has all kinds of
ramifications beyond
what I think he is thinking,
just because

47:31.148 --> 47:32.883 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
he's never been there before.

47:32.916 --> 47:36.720 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You know, I look back at some of
the really
dumb things that I did when I
first became

47:36.753 --> 47:39.790 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
mayor, and maybe it got on the
front page
of The Denver Post.

47:39.823 --> 47:41.525 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But that was -- I could dig
myself out.

47:41.558 --> 47:43.727 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: You attribute
this to rookie
mistakes?

47:43.760 --> 47:44.728 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
GOV.

47:44.761 --> 47:45.729 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JOHN HICKENLOOPER: Yes.

47:45.762 --> 47:47.898 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Well, I think it's a much
broader landscape.

47:47.931 --> 47:53.237 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think he's used to being
able to throw
-- really lobby, push his weight
around.

47:53.270 --> 47:58.775 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You know, the comments to James
Comey, they're
disconcerting.

47:58.809 --> 47:59.743 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
There's no question.

47:59.776 --> 48:00.944 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
But we will see.

48:00.978 --> 48:02.913 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I mean, we don't have all the
information
